Unveiling Supermarket Sales¶

About Datset

Inspired by the dataset available at https://www.kaggle.com/aungpyaeap/supermarket-sales, this project delves into the historical sales records of a supermarket company across three branches over a span of three months.

Overview

  • Conducted comprehensive analysis of a supermarket sales dataset using Pandas and visualization libraries in Python.

  • Cleaned the dataset, handled duplicates, and managed missing values for robust analysis.

  • Explored distributions, variable relationships, branch-wise sales, gender-based spending patterns, and time trends through EDA.

  • Examined correlations between features to unveil underlying relationships within the data.

Libraries

Imported necessary libraries for data analysis and visualization:

  • pandas for data handling,
  • numpy for numerical operations
  • matplotlib and seaborn for visualization,
  • calmap for calendar heatmaps

In [98]:
# Replace NaN values in numeric columns with mean
numeric_columns = df.select_dtypes(include='number').columns
df[numeric_columns] = df[numeric_columns].fillna(df[numeric_columns].mean())

# Replace NaN values in categorical columns with mode
categorical_columns = df.select_dtypes(exclude='number').columns
df[categorical_columns] = df[categorical_columns].fillna(df[categorical_columns].mode().iloc[0])

It seems that, overall, men and women in this dataset spend about the same. However, at the 75th percentile, women tend to spend more than men.

On average, though, their spending appears to be quite similar.
